<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-05">
  <title>Week 5</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-topological-induction">
      <title>Compactness via topological induction</title>
      <p>
        The following technique, <term>topological induction</term>, is an extremely useful proof strategy. In the near term, we will use 
        it to prove that closed intervals of the form <m>[a,b]\subseteq \mathbb R</m> are compact. Later, we will use the same method to 
        show <m>[a,b]</m> is connected, and it can also be used to prove existence and uniqueness of homotopy lifts for covering spaces.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-top-induction">
        <title>Topological induction</title>
        
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>C\subseteq [0,1]</m>  be a subset. Then <m>C=[0,1]</m> if and only if it satisfies the following conditions:
            <dl>
              <li>
                <title>base case</title>
                <p>
                  <m>0\in C</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <title>downward closed</title>
                <p>
                  if <m>t\in C</m> and <m>s\in [0,t]</m>, then <m>s\in C</m>,  
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <title>topological induction</title>
                <p>
                  if <m>t\in C\cap [0,1)</m>, then there exists <m>\varepsilon\gt 0</m> such that <m>t+\varepsilon\in C</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <title>supremal</title>
                <p>
                  <m>\sup C\in C</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </dl>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          It should be clear to the reader that <m>[0,1]</m> satisfies the given conditions. For the converse, suppose that <m>C\subseteq [0,1]</m> 
          satisfies the conditions.
        </p>
        <p>
          By the first condition, <m>C</m> is nonempty. Since <m>C\subseteq [0,1]</m>, we know that <m>C</m> is bounded above by <m>1</m>. By 
          the least upper bound property for <m>\mathbb R</m>, the supremum of <m>C</m> exists and is in <m>[0,1]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>C</m> is downwards closed, we must have <m>C = [0,\sup C)</m> or <m>C = [0,\sup C]</m>. But <m>C</m> is supremal, 
          so <m>C = [0,\sup C]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Finally, the topological induction property ensures that <m>\sup C=1</m>, whence <m>C = [0,1]</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        We now provide the promised application of topological induction.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-compact-closed-intervals">
        <title>Compactness of closed intervals of the real line</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>a\le b</m> are real numbers, then <m>[a,,b]</m> is compact.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          If <m>a=b</m>, then <m>[a,b]=\{a\}</m> is compact since <m>a</m> is necessarily an element of some set in an open cover, and thus is covered 
          by a subcover consisting of a single set.
        </p>
        <p>
          Henceforth, assume <m>a\lt b</m> and let <m>\mathscr U = \{U_i\mid i\in I\}</m> be an open cover of <m>[a,b]</m>. The reader may check the 
          following assertion:
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              Let <m>x\in [a,b)</m>. Then there is an element <m>y\in (x,b]</m> and an element <m>i\in I</m> for which <m>[x,y]\subseteq U_i</m>.
            </p>
          </blockquote>
        </p>
        <p>
          Now let
          <md>
            C := \{y\in [a,b]\mid [a,y]\text{ can be finitely covered by elements of }\mathscr U\}.
          </md>
          We employ topological induction to prove that <m>C = [a,b]</m>, whence <m>[a,b]</m> is compact. The above assertion applied to <m>x=a</m> 
          reveals that <m>a\in C</m>. Downward closure is similarly straightforward: if <m>y\in C</m> and <m>a\le z\le y</m>, then <m>z\in C</m> because 
          a finite subcover of <m>[a,y]</m> is automatically a finite subcover of <m>[a,z]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the topological induction step, suppose that <m>y\in C</m>, meaning that <m>[a,y]</m> can be finitely covered by elements of <m>\mathscr U</m>. 
          Fix a finite subcover of <m>[a,y]</m>. Then <m>y</m> is in some <m>U_i</m> within the finite subcover. But <m>U_i</m> is open, so <m>y+\varepsilon</m> 
          is in <m>U_i</m> for some <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our final task is to show that <m>\sup C\in C</m>. We already know that <m>C = [a,\sup C)</m> or <m>[a,\sup C]</m>. Since <m>\mathscr U</m> is 
          an open cover of <m>[a,b]</m>, there is some index <m>i_0\in I</m> for which <m>\sup C \in U_{i_0}</m>. By openness of <m>U_{i_0}</m>, there exists 
          <m>z\in [a,\sup C)</m> such that <m>(z,\sup C]\subseteq U_{i_0}</m>. By definition of <m>C</m>, <m>[a,z]</m> is finitely covered by <m>\mathscr U</m>. 
          This means there is a finite subset <m>S\subseteq I</m> for which
          <md>
            [a,z]\subseteq \bigcup_{i\in S} U_i.
          </md>
          Thus
          <md>
            [a,\sup C] = [a,z]\cup (z,\sup C]\subseteq \bigg(\bigcup_{i\in S}U_i\bigg)\cup U_{i_0}.
          </md>
          In particular, <m>[a,\sup C]</m> is finitely covered by <m>\mathscr U</m>, so <m>\sup C\in C</m>. By topological induction, <m>C=[a,b]</m>, which 
          concludes our proof.
        </p>
      </proof>
      
      
    </subsubsection>
